Sec. 40001: Authorizes a $24.6 billion special appropriation to the Coast Guard for FY-2025–2029, earmarked for 13 specific procurement and infrastructure items—e.g., $4.3 billion for new Offshore and Polar Security Cutters, $1.1 billion for fixed-wing aircraft, and $4.4 billion for shore facilities including a new dry-dock and boot-camp barracks. The funds are exempt from normal annual caps and must be spent on expedited acquisition processes.

Sec. 40002: Expands the FCC’s spectrum-auction authority through 2034, requires identification of 500 MHz of federal spectrum in the 1.3–10.5 GHz band for reallocation to commercial use (200 MHz by 2027, remainder by 2029), and sets a $50 million Treasury appropriation for supporting analyses and biennial federal spectrum-value reports.

Sec. 40003: Provides $10.97 billion over five years (FY-2025–2029) to the FAA for aviation infrastructure—$4.75 billion for telecom modernization, $3 billion for radar replacement, $1.9 billion for a new ARTCC, $1 billion for TRACON consolidations, and $300 million for remote-tower technology—plus quarterly reporting to Congress.

Sec. 40004: Establishes user-fee schedules for space launches and reentries under the FAA’s Office of Commercial Space Transportation, starting at $30,000 per launch in 2026 and rising to $200,000 by 2033, indexed to CPI, with 70 % of collections deposited into a dedicated fund for licensing operations.

Sec. 40005: Allocates $9.995 billion to NASA for FY-2025–2032, including $4.1 billion for Artemis SLS rockets, $2.6 billion for the Gateway lunar station, $700 million for a commercial Mars telecom orbiter deliverable by 2028, $1.25 billion for ISS operations, and $1 billion for infrastructure upgrades at five NASA centers.

Sec. 40006: Eliminates civil penalties for corporate average fuel-economy non-compliance by reducing the per-vehicle penalties from $5 and $10 to $0, effective immediately for all model years lacking a penalty notification from DOT.

Sec. 40007: Increases the annual lease-payment obligation of the Metropolitan Washington Airports to the U.S. Treasury from $3 million (1987 dollars) to a fixed $15 million per year starting in 2027, with a mandatory 10-year renegotiation clause to maintain that amount.

Sec. 40008: Rescinds any unobligated balances from prior appropriations under sections 40001–40004 of Public Law 117-169, effectively clawing back unspent funds.

Sec. 40009: Cuts the annual federal contribution to the U.S. Travel and Tourism Advisory Board from $100 million to $20 million starting in FY-2025.

Sec. 40010: Rescinds any unobligated balances of the $1.5 billion appropriated under section 40007(a) of Public Law 117-169 for alternative-fuel aviation technology, permanently canceling those funds.

Sec. 40011: Rescinds $850 million of the $1.2 billion provided under section 106(a) of the CHIPS Act of 2022 for the Public Wireless Supply Chain Innovation Fund, leaving $350 million available. [end of text]


